<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0093</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mark A.  Willingham – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I am a semi-retired person living in the Yorkshire Dales National Park. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I have a deep appreciation of the peace and tranquillity and special characteristics of the countryside, and of the benefits that these qualities can offer to all people, not just countryside residents.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">There are many beautiful and potentially peaceful, grassy, unsealed tracks (green lanes) throughout the countryside which are not part of the ordinary roads network (the sealed, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">tarmacadamed</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> motor roads that we all need and take for granted).  These green lanes are part of our natural heritage.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Many of these green lanes currently have no protection from use by recreational off-road vehicles (4x4s and motorbikes) whose owners claim the green lanes are roads and that they have a right to drive along them because in years gone by these lanes were used by horses and carts as ‘roads’.  The ‘off-road’ drivers equate their vehicles to a horse and cart, but of course these modern vehicles are causing massive degradation to the surfaces of these narrow, ancient tracks as their drivers pit them against the environment.  Normal use by other parties, pedestrians, horse riders, pedal cyclists is often made impossible as a result of the surface damage done by the vehicles, which if allowed </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">to continue</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> will in many cases become irreparable. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The noise and sheer presence of recreational off-road vehicles, often in large convoys, on the green lanes destroys the peace and tranquillity of whole areas, with an obvious effect on other users who come into the countryside to enjoy these very characteristics.  Indeed the principle of enabling the public to enjoy the special qualities of these beautiful areas is at the heart of the foundation of National Parks.  In my own area, it has been reported that disturbance by recreational off-road drivers is the biggest single source of complaints to the National Park Authority.   Local, often rare, wildlife is of course also disturbed.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Living in the Yorkshire Dales National Park, I have seen firsthand the damage to the environment caused by the recreational off-road vehicles: beautiful grassy tracks turned into impassable mires, especially in Winter; damage to dry stone walls, gates and fences </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">as  off</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">-roaders break up whatever is at hand to help them get beyond areas of particular track destruction; and tracks forever widening as the drivers seek passable ground to the sides of the impassable original route.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Fortunately the Highways Authority in the Yorkshire Dales National Park, the National Park Authority itself, has seen fit to impose traffic regulation orders on a number of lanes, limiting use to essential users </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> farmers.  Where these orders have been in place for some time, the ground is beginning to recover, but it will take much time for the healing to be </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">complete.  Unfortunately, some lanes, even in the National Park, have no protection and damage and nuisance goes on apace.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">My Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I recommend that the Joint Committee adopt the proposals within the formal submissions of the following organisations Yorkshire Dales Green Lanes Alliance (YDGLA), The Green Lanes Environmental Action Group (GLEAM), The Green Lanes Protection Group (GLPG), and The Peak District Green Lanes Alliance (PDGLA), namely that::</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">All Unsealed Byways Open to All Traffic (BOATS), and all unsealed Unclassified County roads (UCRs) should be recognised as not being part of the ordinary roads network, and should be re-classified as Restricted Byways,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">When a local authority declines to impose a traffic regulation order that is widely-supported by the public, there should be a right of appeal, either to an independent inspector, or a magistrate.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>